{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510167"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:25:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:25:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11500"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11500"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.58,0.21,0.07,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4131"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106179"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4131"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11500"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88653"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5136"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5273"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30107"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33660"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42615"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106179"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department at a small rural hospital with a one-hour history of central crushing chest pain radiating to his jaw, associated with nausea and vomiting. He has a medical history of hypertension, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease with carbon dioxide retention, and type 2 diabetes. He takes regular medications including metformin, ramipril, and inhalers. The nearest cardiac catheterisation laboratory is three hours away by road transport.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed and diaphoretic. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 160/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 91% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His chest is clear to auscultation. A 12-lead ECG shows ST-segment elevation in leads V1, V2, I and aVL with reciprocal changes in III and aVF (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate combination of immediate management steps?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous morphine, oxygen supplementation, and arrange transfer to cardiac catheterisation laboratory","Aspirin, oxygen supplementation, glyceryl trinitrate, intravenous morphine, and arrange fibrinolysis","Aspirin, glyceryl trinitrate, intravenous morphine, and arrange fibrinolysis","Aspirin, glyceryl trinitrate, intravenous fluids, and arrange transfer to cardiac catheterisation laboratory","Aspirin, oxygen supplementation, intravenous fluids, intravenous morphine, and arrange fibrinolysis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an anterior ST-elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) requiring immediate reperfusion therapy. Given the geographical isolation and inability to achieve primary percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) within 120 minutes, immediate fibrinolysis is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patients ECG demonstrates:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EST elevation in leads V1, V2, leads I and aVL\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReciprocal ST depression in lead III and aVF\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese findings are consistent with an antero-lateral STEMI, most likely involving the left main and left anterior descending coronary artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin, glyceryl trinitrate, intravenous morphine, and arrange fibrinolysis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management combination. Aspirin reduces mortality in acute coronary syndrome, glyceryl trinitrate helps with symptom relief, and morphine provides analgesia. Fibrinolysis should be initiated promptly given the distance to PCI facilities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous morphine, oxygen supplementation, and arrange transfer\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as transfer time exceeds 90 minutes, delaying critical reperfusion therapy. Additionally, routine oxygen supplementation is not indicated with an SpO2 of 91%. Current Australian guidelines \u003Cem\u003E(Australian clinical guideline for diagnosing and managing acute coronary syndromes 2025)\u003C/em\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Erecommend oxygen therapy only when oxygen saturation falls below 90%, as hypoxaemia at this level is assumed to contribute to coronary ischaemia. While oxygen therapy is commonly administered when oxygen saturation is 90-92%, its benefit is unknown. In this patient with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and CO2 retention, oxygen therapy could be harmful, and if required, should target an arterial oxygen saturation of approximately 88-92%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin, oxygen supplementation, glyceryl trinitrate, intravenous morphine, and arrange fibrinolysis\u003C/strong\u003E includes unnecessary oxygen therapy which could be harmful in this patient with CO2 retention and provides no proven benefit at this oxygen saturation level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin, glyceryl trinitrate, intravenous fluids, and arrange transfer\u003C/strong\u003E delays reperfusion therapy and includes unnecessary fluid administration in a normotensive patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin, oxygen supplementation, intravenous fluids, intravenous morphine, and arrange fibrinolysis\u003C/strong\u003E includes both unnecessary oxygen and fluid administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initiating fibrinolysis, the patient should be transferred to a PCI-capable facility within 24 hours for coronary angiography. If there are signs of failed reperfusion, immediate transfer for rescue PCI would be indicated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Immediate fibrinolysis is indicated for STEMI when primary PCI cannot be achieved within 90 minutes of first medical contact.","Supplemental oxygen should only be given to patients with acute coronary syndrome if their SpO2 is less than 90%.","Initial STEMI management includes aspirin, glyceryl trinitrate, and analgesia, followed by timely reperfusion therapy."],"references":["National Heart Foundation of Australia, Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand. Australian clinical guideline for diagnosing and managing acute coronary syndromes 2025. 2025. Available at: https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/for-professionals/acs-guideline","Nickson C. Oxygen and carbon dioxide retention in COPD [Internet]. Life in the Fast Lane \u2022 LITFL. 2019 [cited 2022 Jan 18]. Available from: https://litfl.com/oxygen-and-carbon-dioxide-retention-in-copd/","Antman EM, Anbe DT, Armstrong PW, Bates ER, Green LA, Hand M, et al. ACC/AHA guidelines for the management of patients with ST-elevation myocardial infarction--executive summary: a report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Practice Guidelines (Writing Committee to Revise the 1999 Guidelines for the Management of Patients With Acute Myocardial Infarction): A report of the American college of cardiology/American heart association task force on practice guidelines (writing committee to revise the 1999 guidelines for the management of patients with acute myocardial infarction). Circulation [Internet]. 2004;110(5):588\u2013636. Available from: http://dx.doi.org/10.1161/01.CIR.0000134791.68010.FEd Burns and Robert Buttner, \u0022Anterior Myocardial Infarction,\u0022 In: LITFL - Life in the FastLane, Accessed on January 16, 2022, https://litfl.com/anterior-myocardial-infarction-ecg-library/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88653"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11500"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16883"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16883"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/50a2a23f-b7b2-4867-8374-4bedf850825a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/50a2a23f-b7b2-4867-8374-4bedf850825a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":355}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88653"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-16T17:27:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-17T16:09:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4131"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106179"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici